SPEAKER: I don't want to make
the assumption that everyone

00:00:08.080 --> 00:00:09.700
knows what Reddit is.

00:00:09.700 --> 00:00:12.140
I think most of this room will.

00:00:12.140 --> 00:00:14.770
But I thought there was a
really great quote in your book

00:00:14.770 --> 00:00:15.580
that kind of described it.

00:00:15.580 --> 00:00:17.710
So I want to describe it
from the book that you wrote.

00:00:17.710 --> 00:00:19.084
And then I want
to hear your take

00:00:19.084 --> 00:00:20.732
on how you would
describe it to someone

00:00:20.732 --> 00:00:21.940
who's never been to the site.

00:00:21.940 --> 00:00:24.280
So the quote is, "Being
in love with someone

00:00:24.280 --> 00:00:27.340
who has a constantly
expanding and mostly beautiful

00:00:27.340 --> 00:00:28.929
multiple personality disorder."

00:00:28.929 --> 00:00:30.220
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN: Yes.

00:00:30.220 --> 00:00:31.960
SPEAKER: How would
you describe Reddit?

00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:35.230
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN:
Well, in standard interviews,

00:00:35.230 --> 00:00:38.050
for folks who actually
have no clue about Reddit,

00:00:38.050 --> 00:00:41.830
I say, it's sort of a mirror
of the entire internet.

00:00:41.830 --> 00:00:44.530
It's kind of a
bulletin board site

00:00:44.530 --> 00:00:46.480
with everything under the sun.

00:00:46.480 --> 00:00:47.890
It's got the day's news.

00:00:47.890 --> 00:00:49.750
It's got every shiny meme.

00:00:49.750 --> 00:00:54.100
It's got every conspiracy
theory, anything

00:00:54.100 --> 00:00:55.887
you can imagine, you know?

00:00:55.887 --> 00:00:56.470
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:00:56.470 --> 00:00:57.970
So let's dig into--

00:00:57.970 --> 00:00:59.710
you're a full-time journalist.

00:00:59.710 --> 00:01:02.290
When did you decide to take
on the challenge of a book?

00:01:02.290 --> 00:01:04.420
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN:
Well, so this

00:01:04.420 --> 00:01:07.600
is kind of a funny
story, because I

00:01:07.600 --> 00:01:09.490
took on the idea of
this book before it

00:01:09.490 --> 00:01:10.990
was a good idea for a book.

00:01:10.990 --> 00:01:13.900
I mean, it was back in 2011.

00:01:13.900 --> 00:01:17.830
And I was a young journalist
working at "Inc." magazine.

00:01:17.830 --> 00:01:21.340
And I met with Alexis
Ohanian and Steve Hoffman

00:01:21.340 --> 00:01:23.830
on a total whim at
South by Southwest.

00:01:23.830 --> 00:01:26.200
And they were, at
the time, working

00:01:26.200 --> 00:01:30.040
on a site called Hipmunk,
which is a travel search

00:01:30.040 --> 00:01:33.730
site like Kayak, only
it searches sites

00:01:33.730 --> 00:01:36.340
based on the agony they
would induce on the user

00:01:36.340 --> 00:01:39.340
rather than, say, price.

00:01:39.340 --> 00:01:43.690
And I wasn't that interested
in their little travel site.

00:01:43.690 --> 00:01:46.960
I was interested in the fact
that these two seemingly normal

00:01:46.960 --> 00:01:50.974
guys built Reddit, which, at
the time, was in the news for--

00:01:50.974 --> 00:01:51.640
I think it was--

00:01:51.640 --> 00:01:53.764
I can't remember if it was
either jailbait or creep

00:01:53.764 --> 00:01:56.900
shots or a combination of both.

00:01:56.900 --> 00:01:59.950
But it also was sort
of known already

00:01:59.950 --> 00:02:02.050
as the internet's
virality engine.

00:02:02.050 --> 00:02:04.997
It was something that,
when one of our articles--

00:02:04.997 --> 00:02:06.580
as a journalist,
when an article would

00:02:06.580 --> 00:02:10.495
reach the front page of Reddit
or even the top of a news

00:02:10.495 --> 00:02:13.780
subreddit or something, it
would send so much traffic.

00:02:13.780 --> 00:02:16.750
We called it the
Reddit hug of death

00:02:16.750 --> 00:02:18.330
that it would
cripple our servers,

00:02:18.330 --> 00:02:19.830
but, you know, give
so much traffic.

00:02:19.830 --> 00:02:21.860
So I wanted to know
more about Reddit.

00:02:21.860 --> 00:02:26.220
And I didn't get to know
that day, all the stories.

00:02:26.220 --> 00:02:29.440
But turns out, Alexis Ohanian
lived in Brooklyn, as did I.

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:32.152
And we were able to meet
up on Atlantic Avenue,

00:02:32.152 --> 00:02:32.860
have some coffee.

00:02:32.860 --> 00:02:36.310
So I heard the whole story and
thought, this is fantastic.

00:02:36.310 --> 00:02:38.800
Just what they went through
in the first year of building

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:41.800
it alone was such a
scrappy, great, garage

00:02:41.800 --> 00:02:44.880
building-a-startup story
that I pitched them both.

00:02:44.880 --> 00:02:48.370
I pitched Steve and Alexis
on exclusively talking to me

00:02:48.370 --> 00:02:49.910
for the purpose of a book.

00:02:49.910 --> 00:02:52.372
And so it's been years,
years in the making.

00:02:52.372 --> 00:02:53.830
SPEAKER: So you
kind of met halfway

00:02:53.830 --> 00:02:55.120
through where it is today.

00:02:55.120 --> 00:02:55.920
CHRISTINE
LAGORIO-CHAFKIN: Oh, yeah.

00:02:55.920 --> 00:02:58.187
And none of the crazy recent
stuff had happened yet.

00:02:58.187 --> 00:02:58.770
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:02:58.770 --> 00:03:01.630
And you're at a place that it's
also a start-in-a-garage kind

00:03:01.630 --> 00:03:03.160
of really interesting start.

00:03:03.160 --> 00:03:05.764
So when you started to
uncover the history of Reddit,

00:03:05.764 --> 00:03:07.180
you started digging
into the book,

00:03:07.180 --> 00:03:09.880
what was that look-back
to that first,

00:03:09.880 --> 00:03:12.714
kind of, beginning years
of how this site spawned

00:03:12.714 --> 00:03:13.630
into what it is today?

00:03:13.630 --> 00:03:15.005
CHRISTINE
LAGORIO-CHAFKIN: Right.

00:03:15.005 --> 00:03:18.550
Well, those are kind of the
nice, friendly, gentle times.

00:03:18.550 --> 00:03:22.600
And it was fascinating to look
back because you see the seeds

00:03:22.600 --> 00:03:28.090
of how virality works and how
things-- just little ideas--

00:03:28.090 --> 00:03:31.660
can take off online in ways
that we had never seen before.

00:03:31.660 --> 00:03:33.250
So I mean, from one of--

00:03:33.250 --> 00:03:35.431
Reddit has two magic
secret sauces, right?

00:03:35.431 --> 00:03:36.430
They're not even secret.

00:03:36.430 --> 00:03:39.850
But there's the algorithm
that powers the front page

00:03:39.850 --> 00:03:42.700
and everything on the
site, from every comment

00:03:42.700 --> 00:03:44.310
and how the threads
are threaded,

00:03:44.310 --> 00:03:47.050
to just how stuff
bubbles to the front page

00:03:47.050 --> 00:03:49.900
and how much time it is
allotted to stay there.

00:03:49.900 --> 00:03:53.680
Then, that's coupled with
the fact that moderators--

00:03:53.680 --> 00:03:56.800
well, basically anyone on the
planet can start a subreddit.

00:03:56.800 --> 00:03:59.230
But then, you have to
take on the responsibility

00:03:59.230 --> 00:04:00.320
of running that thing.

00:04:00.320 --> 00:04:02.650
You are responsible
for its content

00:04:02.650 --> 00:04:08.560
and for maintaining the rules of
that little fraction of Reddit.

00:04:08.560 --> 00:04:10.600
So having thousands
upon thousands

00:04:10.600 --> 00:04:13.719
of volunteer moderators paired
with that algorithm, I think,

00:04:13.719 --> 00:04:15.010
is what made Reddit so special.

00:04:15.010 --> 00:04:18.970
And then it allowed us to
see, in the early days, things

00:04:18.970 --> 00:04:20.000
like--

00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:23.170
there was this great story
called Mr. Splashy Pants.

00:04:23.170 --> 00:04:26.350
Are any of you guys familiar
with Mr. Splashy Pants?

00:04:26.350 --> 00:04:26.850
OK.

00:04:26.850 --> 00:04:28.750
If you've heard
Alexis speak, you've

00:04:28.750 --> 00:04:31.430
heard this story, probably,
because he loves to tell it.

00:04:31.430 --> 00:04:33.490
But it really was one
of the first moments

00:04:33.490 --> 00:04:37.120
where you could see, OK, this
formula on Reddit is working.

00:04:37.120 --> 00:04:39.760
And when something
becomes popular on Reddit,

00:04:39.760 --> 00:04:43.450
its ready for mainstream
viewing by everyone else.

00:04:43.450 --> 00:04:46.770
What had happened was
Greenpeace decided

00:04:46.770 --> 00:04:50.170
to-- they were trying
to just basically build

00:04:50.170 --> 00:04:53.800
some community online
around whale support

00:04:53.800 --> 00:04:57.370
and earn money for tracking
more whales avoiding

00:04:57.370 --> 00:04:59.050
Japanese harpooning.

00:04:59.050 --> 00:05:02.650
And they decided to open up
a contest for the internet,

00:05:02.650 --> 00:05:04.750
in general, to name a whale.

00:05:04.750 --> 00:05:09.460
And there were beautiful names
that people had submitted.

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:12.220
I think one was
Kaimana, which means--

00:05:12.220 --> 00:05:13.350
I forget exactly.

00:05:13.350 --> 00:05:15.370
It means something.

00:05:15.370 --> 00:05:18.040
It means, like, lovely
creature of the sea.

00:05:18.040 --> 00:05:21.880
And someone posted
to Reddit, hey,

00:05:21.880 --> 00:05:24.670
Greenpeace is doing this
campaign to name a whale.

00:05:24.670 --> 00:05:27.966
Let's name him
Mr. Splashy Pants.

00:05:27.966 --> 00:05:29.840
Go to the site and vote
up Mr. Splashy Pants.

00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:31.509
So of course,
redditors did en masse.

00:05:31.509 --> 00:05:32.550
So did people from 4chan.

00:05:32.550 --> 00:05:34.420
So did lots of folks.

00:05:34.420 --> 00:05:38.230
And Greenpeace was
not happy about this.

00:05:38.230 --> 00:05:42.220
But Mr. Splashy Pants did win.

00:05:42.220 --> 00:05:45.310
And then for a while, Greenpeace
had a really good merch

00:05:45.310 --> 00:05:48.700
business on its
hands with that one.

00:05:48.700 --> 00:05:51.707
SPEAKER: So we'll get into some
of the virality of the site

00:05:51.707 --> 00:05:53.540
and some of good and
bad that comes with it.

00:05:53.540 --> 00:05:56.352
But looking back at,
from where it started

00:05:56.352 --> 00:05:58.810
to where it is today, what was
the part of the history that

00:05:58.810 --> 00:06:00.961
surprised you most?

00:06:00.961 --> 00:06:03.460
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN: Well,
I mean, the business story.

00:06:03.460 --> 00:06:05.230
I'm a business journalist.

00:06:05.230 --> 00:06:09.730
The story of Reddit sustaining
itself through the years

00:06:09.730 --> 00:06:13.120
was just consistently the most
surprising and fascinating

00:06:13.120 --> 00:06:13.760
story to me.

00:06:13.760 --> 00:06:16.990
I think that's one that's
little known, as well.

00:06:16.990 --> 00:06:20.440
So Reddit was acquired
just more than a year

00:06:20.440 --> 00:06:21.550
after it was created.

00:06:21.550 --> 00:06:25.050
It was acquired by Condé Nast
whose parent company is Advance

00:06:25.050 --> 00:06:26.420
Publications.

00:06:26.420 --> 00:06:29.360
They're known for their
shiny, glossy magazines.

00:06:29.360 --> 00:06:30.430
Now, Reddit is not that.

00:06:30.430 --> 00:06:34.120
But it was acquired for a
little more than $10 million.

00:06:34.120 --> 00:06:38.770
And after that point, Reddit
was put into the "Wired" office

00:06:38.770 --> 00:06:39.760
in San Francisco.

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:41.060
The guys moved out there.

00:06:41.060 --> 00:06:45.160
There's four to six of them at
a time in a little conference

00:06:45.160 --> 00:06:47.050
room in "Wired."

00:06:47.050 --> 00:06:50.020
And they were sort of left to
build the site on their own.

00:06:50.020 --> 00:06:53.740
And miraculously, that worked.

00:06:53.740 --> 00:06:57.550
The Newhouse family that runs
Condé was pretty hands-off with

00:06:57.550 --> 00:06:58.870
them.

00:06:58.870 --> 00:07:01.942
They had quarterly
meetings and shared goals

00:07:01.942 --> 00:07:02.900
and that sort of thing.

00:07:02.900 --> 00:07:06.010
But otherwise, it was just
left to its own devices.

00:07:06.010 --> 00:07:09.010
And somehow, it worked.

00:07:09.010 --> 00:07:12.170
When Steve and Alexis, the
two founders, left Reddit,

00:07:12.170 --> 00:07:12.730
it worked.

00:07:12.730 --> 00:07:15.910
There was amazing growth in
the year after they left.

00:07:15.910 --> 00:07:20.890
When Condé Nast spun out
Reddit from Condé into Advance

00:07:20.890 --> 00:07:23.470
Publications, basically allowing
it to operate like a Silicon

00:07:23.470 --> 00:07:25.350
Valley company
and take VC money,

00:07:25.350 --> 00:07:28.420
which it subsequently
did, that still worked.

00:07:28.420 --> 00:07:29.440
They got a new CEO.

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:33.100
They just put in a total
outsider named Yishan Wong.

00:07:33.100 --> 00:07:36.974
And the site kept growing
and growing and growing,

00:07:36.974 --> 00:07:39.140
and even operating under a
different business model.

00:07:39.140 --> 00:07:43.560
So watching that unfold, I
think, it was just incredible.

00:07:43.560 --> 00:07:47.061
And Yishan made some very
bizarre business decisions

00:07:47.061 --> 00:07:47.810
during his tenure.

00:07:47.810 --> 00:07:48.520
SPEAKER: Yeah.

00:07:48.520 --> 00:07:50.103
That was going to
be my next question.

00:07:50.103 --> 00:07:53.380
So when Alexis and
Steve left, there

00:07:53.380 --> 00:07:56.150
was a period where
he was in charge.

00:07:56.150 --> 00:07:57.400
And there's a lot in the book.

00:07:57.400 --> 00:07:59.780
And the book goes into
the history of everything,

00:07:59.780 --> 00:08:01.900
so I highly recommend it.

00:08:01.900 --> 00:08:03.520
What were some of
those decisions

00:08:03.520 --> 00:08:07.450
that they had to turn back
that you kind of uncovered?

00:08:07.450 --> 00:08:09.610
And now, with looking
at where they are today,

00:08:09.610 --> 00:08:12.216
how that section of the business
really took it to, again,

00:08:12.216 --> 00:08:13.090
where they are today?

00:08:13.090 --> 00:08:14.420
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN: Yeah.

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:16.169
Well, I think the
funniest one is actually

00:08:16.169 --> 00:08:19.840
before Yishan came
in, when the guys were

00:08:19.840 --> 00:08:21.370
unable to hire anyone.

00:08:21.370 --> 00:08:23.620
There were four guys just
basically working on Reddit.

00:08:23.620 --> 00:08:25.270
And they wanted anyone.

00:08:25.270 --> 00:08:27.280
They wanted just
another programmer.

00:08:27.280 --> 00:08:31.240
And Condé Nast told them, well,
if you bump up your revenue,

00:08:31.240 --> 00:08:33.710
make $1 million for us next
year, you can hire someone.

00:08:33.710 --> 00:08:37.510
And they were just looking
at each other like, what?

00:08:37.510 --> 00:08:41.559
And so instead of just
shuffling their feet,

00:08:41.559 --> 00:08:44.830
they decided to wait for a
summer Friday when they assumed

00:08:44.830 --> 00:08:47.920
that most Condé executives
would be off in the Hamptons.

00:08:47.920 --> 00:08:52.300
And they launched a thing
called Reddit Gold, which

00:08:52.300 --> 00:08:55.810
basically allowed people
to give them donations.

00:08:55.810 --> 00:08:57.310
It was sort of a
subscription model.

00:08:57.310 --> 00:08:59.476
But there wasn't-- they
didn't really offer anything

00:08:59.476 --> 00:09:01.390
in exchange for the money yet.

00:09:01.390 --> 00:09:03.640
And they turned the thing on.

00:09:03.640 --> 00:09:06.910
And nobody at Condé was pissed
because they didn't notice

00:09:06.910 --> 00:09:07.410
at first.

00:09:07.410 --> 00:09:10.780
But by Monday, they had raised
so much money that no one

00:09:10.780 --> 00:09:14.524
at Condé was upset.

00:09:14.524 --> 00:09:15.440
So it actually worked.

00:09:15.440 --> 00:09:18.700
And I mean, I--

00:09:18.700 --> 00:09:20.830
a funny-- a little
known fact about this--

00:09:20.830 --> 00:09:23.710
Steve Hoffman, who's
the CEO of Reddit now,

00:09:23.710 --> 00:09:25.760
was not at Reddit at the time.

00:09:25.760 --> 00:09:29.200
And he told me later,
much, much later,

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:30.700
when I was asking
him about this--

00:09:30.700 --> 00:09:32.222
he said he was
watching from afar.

00:09:32.222 --> 00:09:34.430
And he thought it was a
little embarrassing that they

00:09:34.430 --> 00:09:36.357
had stooped to this level.

00:09:36.357 --> 00:09:37.690
These guys were all his friends.

00:09:37.690 --> 00:09:39.220
But they turned on Reddit Gold.

00:09:39.220 --> 00:09:42.130
And I said, well,
it worked though.

00:09:42.130 --> 00:09:48.280
And he looked at me and said,
well, it didn't not work.

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:50.200
SPEAKER: So that's
an interesting piece.

00:09:50.200 --> 00:09:52.360
A lot of when you read
the book, you realize

00:09:52.360 --> 00:09:53.950
that it doesn't
seem like everything

00:09:53.950 --> 00:09:56.000
was always very
well thought out.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:58.730
It was more of a-- they
kind of had to just roll

00:09:58.730 --> 00:09:59.700
with what happened.

00:09:59.700 --> 00:10:00.043
CHRISTINE
LAGORIO-CHAFKIN: Right.

00:10:00.043 --> 00:10:00.386
Yeah.

00:10:00.386 --> 00:10:02.011
SPEAKER: How do you
think that-- again,

00:10:02.011 --> 00:10:04.920
how does that shape where
we are today in the business

00:10:04.920 --> 00:10:05.880
side of the history?

00:10:05.880 --> 00:10:07.530
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN:
Well, I actually think more

00:10:07.530 --> 00:10:09.780
interesting than the business
side of the history is--

00:10:09.780 --> 00:10:13.080
and I can get to that too-- but
is the social side of things.

00:10:13.080 --> 00:10:14.860
How did it shape
internet culture today?

00:10:14.860 --> 00:10:16.830
And how did it shape
what Reddit became?

00:10:16.830 --> 00:10:18.246
I mean, you think
about how Reddit

00:10:18.246 --> 00:10:20.430
was founded as sort
of this freedom

00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:24.570
from the press, a place
where users have the power

00:10:24.570 --> 00:10:26.730
to upvote and downvote
things and determine

00:10:26.730 --> 00:10:30.690
what's on the top of every home
page rather than an editor.

00:10:30.690 --> 00:10:33.990
That, sort of, was
taken to its extreme

00:10:33.990 --> 00:10:36.840
by this community, which
was left to its own devices

00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:38.220
during those years.

00:10:38.220 --> 00:10:43.320
And users on the site loved to
push and prod at those limits.

00:10:43.320 --> 00:10:45.190
What was the limit
of free speech?

00:10:45.190 --> 00:10:47.910
What is the limit of
what we can get away

00:10:47.910 --> 00:10:52.860
with in terms of gore and
anything-- pornography,

00:10:52.860 --> 00:10:55.410
and animal abuse,
like, a highway crash?

00:10:55.410 --> 00:10:57.870
It's like, what's the
limit of what's allowed?

00:10:57.870 --> 00:10:59.860
And that's why,
during those years,

00:10:59.860 --> 00:11:04.080
the community spiraled
out of control at times.

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:06.700
On the business
side, I would say,

00:11:06.700 --> 00:11:11.850
Reddit's kind of been in debt
to itself for years, right?

00:11:11.850 --> 00:11:12.690
As soon as--

00:11:12.690 --> 00:11:15.020
Steve Huffman came
back more than,

00:11:15.020 --> 00:11:17.940
I guess, three years ago as CEO.

00:11:17.940 --> 00:11:22.170
And he still has his work
cut out for him, right?

00:11:22.170 --> 00:11:27.420
The site had taken $50 million
in venture capital at that time

00:11:27.420 --> 00:11:29.700
and now has taken
a great deal more.

00:11:29.700 --> 00:11:31.200
But he had to hire
up from something

00:11:31.200 --> 00:11:36.600
like 20-some people, after a
bunch left after he returned,

00:11:36.600 --> 00:11:39.990
to the more than
400 it has today.

00:11:39.990 --> 00:11:41.880
And that's before you
even start working

00:11:41.880 --> 00:11:45.300
on those noxious content issues
and building in really reliable

00:11:45.300 --> 00:11:46.934
advertising to the site.

00:11:46.934 --> 00:11:48.600
SPEAKER: So I want
to pivot a little bit

00:11:48.600 --> 00:11:50.460
to another player
besides-- obviously,

00:11:50.460 --> 00:11:51.917
Alexis and Steve
are the main two.

00:11:51.917 --> 00:11:53.250
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN: Yeah.

00:11:53.250 --> 00:11:54.606
SPEAKER: There's one who kind
of weaves their way in and out

00:11:54.606 --> 00:11:55.890
of this book a lot,
almost to the point

00:11:55.890 --> 00:11:58.050
where you got to remember
it's not fiction--

00:11:58.050 --> 00:12:00.990
is Aaron Swartz.

00:12:00.990 --> 00:12:04.490
So what was his role early on?

00:12:04.490 --> 00:12:06.850
And then obviously, he
kind of had a sad ending

00:12:06.850 --> 00:12:11.190
with suicide towards the
end of his time with Reddit.

00:12:11.190 --> 00:12:13.470
It's a big part of his story.

00:12:13.470 --> 00:12:17.070
So what was it like hearing
people talk about his time

00:12:17.070 --> 00:12:18.160
at the company?

00:12:18.160 --> 00:12:19.868
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN:
I have to say,

00:12:19.868 --> 00:12:23.430
as a reporter, that was one of
the most interesting threads

00:12:23.430 --> 00:12:26.310
to pull, and then, as a
writer, one of the most

00:12:26.310 --> 00:12:28.822
complicated stories to tell.

00:12:28.822 --> 00:12:30.780
One of the great things
about writing this book

00:12:30.780 --> 00:12:35.280
was that every person in it
is a super complex character.

00:12:35.280 --> 00:12:39.810
Nobody is as they seem on
the surface at first, right?

00:12:39.810 --> 00:12:41.670
Because you've got
Alexis Ohanian,

00:12:41.670 --> 00:12:44.370
who's a great showman
and a charismatic dude.

00:12:44.370 --> 00:12:47.220
But he's gone through some
really troubling times

00:12:47.220 --> 00:12:48.340
personally.

00:12:48.340 --> 00:12:51.270
And then you've got
Aaron Swartz, who--

00:12:51.270 --> 00:12:56.860
I always held him up as sort of
this early internet wunderkind.

00:12:56.860 --> 00:12:59.700
He was this great
hacker with a heart.

00:12:59.700 --> 00:13:04.170
And he obviously
had a tragic end.

00:13:04.170 --> 00:13:06.240
And I thought this was
a fascinating story.

00:13:06.240 --> 00:13:09.060
But then I started to hear
about the early days at Reddit.

00:13:09.060 --> 00:13:13.470
When he was just 19
years old, he basically

00:13:13.470 --> 00:13:15.210
stumbled into
working for Reddit.

00:13:15.210 --> 00:13:16.949
Paul Graham, who
started Y Combinator,

00:13:16.949 --> 00:13:18.990
suggested that he started
working with those guys

00:13:18.990 --> 00:13:21.240
because his own startup
sort of floundered.

00:13:21.240 --> 00:13:23.370
And he did.

00:13:23.370 --> 00:13:26.750
And he and Steve rewrote
the site into Python.

00:13:26.750 --> 00:13:31.170
And then, after that, I
started hearing that he just

00:13:31.170 --> 00:13:34.290
sort of gradually
stopped working on Reddit

00:13:34.290 --> 00:13:36.450
and started writing
a book on childhood

00:13:36.450 --> 00:13:39.000
development in his room.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:42.990
And this all--
their relationship

00:13:42.990 --> 00:13:44.460
got really fractured.

00:13:44.460 --> 00:13:47.430
And I thought, god, this
is such a tricky story

00:13:47.430 --> 00:13:51.150
to write because he's
someone so beloved.

00:13:51.150 --> 00:13:52.650
And then to hear that--

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:55.830
I heard from many sources that
he was one of the reasons that

00:13:55.830 --> 00:13:58.710
they sold the company so
early, is they couldn't--

00:13:58.710 --> 00:14:02.200
they all couldn't
work together anymore.

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:05.561
And then Aaron left shortly
after the acquisition.

00:14:05.561 --> 00:14:07.560
It was sort of amazing
that he even stuck around

00:14:07.560 --> 00:14:09.720
that long, I learned.

00:14:09.720 --> 00:14:11.920
And I do think he loved Reddit.

00:14:11.920 --> 00:14:14.670
I do think that part of
Reddit's original spirit--

00:14:14.670 --> 00:14:16.160
and it's sustaining.

00:14:16.160 --> 00:14:19.710
Its spirit to this day was sort
of that hacker with a glint

00:14:19.710 --> 00:14:25.550
in his eye, that trouble-maker,
information-wants-to-be-free

00:14:25.550 --> 00:14:28.830
sort of activist
behind a screen.

00:14:28.830 --> 00:14:31.230
And you can see a
little bit of his sense

00:14:31.230 --> 00:14:34.410
of humor and his
passion still in the way

00:14:34.410 --> 00:14:36.730
the site thinks today.

00:14:36.730 --> 00:14:39.840
Similarly, you can see Steve
Huffman's sense of humor

00:14:39.840 --> 00:14:40.830
in the site--

00:14:40.830 --> 00:14:45.010
that trollish, nothing is
as it seems on the surface--

00:14:45.010 --> 00:14:46.619
that's Steve, for sure.

00:14:46.619 --> 00:14:48.660
SPEAKER: So you mentioned
the complex characters.

00:14:48.660 --> 00:14:52.182
As you interviewed a lot of
different people for this book,

00:14:52.182 --> 00:14:53.640
how did you piece
together what you

00:14:53.640 --> 00:14:55.920
would hear from the person
versus what you're hearing

00:14:55.920 --> 00:14:57.900
from somebody else
explaining, sometimes

00:14:57.900 --> 00:15:00.180
the same story, but hearing
very different things,

00:15:00.180 --> 00:15:02.559
to kind of piece together
what was the reality?

00:15:02.559 --> 00:15:04.600
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN:
Well, as a journalist,

00:15:04.600 --> 00:15:09.380
there are certain layers of
how deep you can go, right?

00:15:09.380 --> 00:15:12.710
If I'm just working on a
daily news story or something,

00:15:12.710 --> 00:15:18.140
I just take what is said and
what is facts at, kind of,

00:15:18.140 --> 00:15:18.680
face value.

00:15:18.680 --> 00:15:20.720
When you're working on
a narrative like this,

00:15:20.720 --> 00:15:23.120
it's so much deeper
because you have

00:15:23.120 --> 00:15:25.310
to try to get as
many perspectives

00:15:25.310 --> 00:15:28.130
on a situation as possible.

00:15:28.130 --> 00:15:31.130
There are certain scenes
from the book that I was not

00:15:31.130 --> 00:15:33.350
present at, that read
like I was present at,

00:15:33.350 --> 00:15:35.480
because I've spoken
to so many people

00:15:35.480 --> 00:15:37.580
about that moment in time.

00:15:37.580 --> 00:15:39.950
There are others, by the way,
that I was not present at,

00:15:39.950 --> 00:15:43.040
that I simply could put together
from a photograph or a video

00:15:43.040 --> 00:15:44.600
or something.

00:15:44.600 --> 00:15:45.330
It's amazing.

00:15:45.330 --> 00:15:46.746
This is a book
about the internet.

00:15:46.746 --> 00:15:50.600
And the internet is just
riches of documentation.

00:15:50.600 --> 00:15:54.320
The research was so
fun and so interesting

00:15:54.320 --> 00:15:57.720
at times because I could
see a photo from a day

00:15:57.720 --> 00:15:59.720
and put it together with
what people had told me

00:15:59.720 --> 00:16:01.610
and read someone's
blog post about it

00:16:01.610 --> 00:16:04.890
and check out the Reddit
threads from that moment as well

00:16:04.890 --> 00:16:07.160
and then piece
everything together.

00:16:07.160 --> 00:16:12.620
That said, not every
source agrees with itself.

00:16:12.620 --> 00:16:16.740
There were certain facts
that one person would just

00:16:16.740 --> 00:16:17.780
disagree with.

00:16:17.780 --> 00:16:20.420
And because I was
reporting on things

00:16:20.420 --> 00:16:22.640
at times that happened
12 years ago--

00:16:22.640 --> 00:16:23.810
memories are all different.

00:16:23.810 --> 00:16:30.740
I learned so much about how the
human brain and memories work.

00:16:30.740 --> 00:16:32.300
Everyone is so
different in terms

00:16:32.300 --> 00:16:38.940
of how they process information
and which pieces they retain.

00:16:38.940 --> 00:16:41.870
So I really had to
weigh heavily on people

00:16:41.870 --> 00:16:47.600
whose memories were kind of
trust-- were lined up at times.

00:16:47.600 --> 00:16:50.960
And then I knew that their
other ones would line up as well

00:16:50.960 --> 00:16:53.230
or I could weigh a
little more heavily.

00:16:53.230 --> 00:16:56.022
Or I could lean on
them more heavily.

00:16:56.022 --> 00:16:57.980
SPEAKER: So I want to
switch gears a little bit

00:16:57.980 --> 00:16:59.430
to the social aspects
that you mentioned.

00:16:59.430 --> 00:16:59.695
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN: Sure.

00:16:59.695 --> 00:17:02.810
SPEAKER: Reddit's obviously--
has a very interesting social

00:17:02.810 --> 00:17:03.800
aspect of it--

00:17:03.800 --> 00:17:04.736
some good, some bad.

00:17:04.736 --> 00:17:07.069
I want to get into a couple
that you cover in the book--

00:17:07.069 --> 00:17:08.390
some good, some bad.

00:17:08.390 --> 00:17:09.829
Which would you prefer
to go first, good or bad?

00:17:09.829 --> 00:17:10.520
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN:
Oh, I don't care.

00:17:10.520 --> 00:17:11.030
Up to you.

00:17:11.030 --> 00:17:11.480
Up to you.

00:17:11.480 --> 00:17:11.980
SPEAKER: OK.

00:17:11.980 --> 00:17:13.520
Let's start with the bad first.

00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:14.000
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN:
All right.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:15.050
SPEAKER: And then, we
will be a little bit more

00:17:15.050 --> 00:17:15.869
uplifting after.

00:17:15.869 --> 00:17:21.020
I think the doxing, which
is sharing someone's

00:17:21.020 --> 00:17:22.670
personal information online--

00:17:22.670 --> 00:17:24.230
and I think the
moment that it really

00:17:24.230 --> 00:17:27.140
highlights in the book is with
the Boston Bombing suspects.

00:17:27.140 --> 00:17:30.890
So what was it like looking
back on that national, almost

00:17:30.890 --> 00:17:34.140
global history moment, and how
Reddit's played a huge part

00:17:34.140 --> 00:17:34.640
in it?

00:17:34.640 --> 00:17:35.973
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN: Yeah.

00:17:35.973 --> 00:17:37.820
When the Boston
Marathon happened,

00:17:37.820 --> 00:17:39.530
I was actually
working at CBS News.

00:17:39.530 --> 00:17:41.540
I was a writer for Katie Couric.

00:17:41.540 --> 00:17:45.602
And so if you're
in a newsroom, you

00:17:45.602 --> 00:17:47.060
sit with a computer
in front of you

00:17:47.060 --> 00:17:49.250
and a row of TVs
above your head.

00:17:49.250 --> 00:17:52.580
And I sat there just
watching everything.

00:17:52.580 --> 00:17:54.500
And we were reporting
on it simultaneously,

00:17:54.500 --> 00:17:55.520
as everyone else was.

00:17:55.520 --> 00:17:59.630
And this was, I think, America's
introduction to Reddit.

00:17:59.630 --> 00:18:03.020
This was the time our parents
first heard about the site

00:18:03.020 --> 00:18:05.810
because it was actually
a bunch of reporters

00:18:05.810 --> 00:18:07.520
who were tweeting
stuff from Reddit

00:18:07.520 --> 00:18:11.060
and spreading around little
bits of misinformation

00:18:11.060 --> 00:18:14.390
that they didn't
know were unreliable

00:18:14.390 --> 00:18:19.640
that fed, that kind of fed the
beast and fed that hype cycle.

00:18:19.640 --> 00:18:23.870
And the news moved
so fast that--

00:18:23.870 --> 00:18:26.970
it was a tricky thing
because Reddit had actually

00:18:26.970 --> 00:18:29.700
solved crimes in the past.

00:18:29.700 --> 00:18:33.380
It's the place where
you go if you get hit.

00:18:33.380 --> 00:18:35.420
If your vehicle's parked
and gets hit and run,

00:18:35.420 --> 00:18:37.378
and you've got a little
piece of the tail light

00:18:37.378 --> 00:18:40.020
of the other car, someone
out there on Reddit

00:18:40.020 --> 00:18:41.581
will identify that.

00:18:41.581 --> 00:18:43.580
And you can give that to
your police department.

00:18:43.580 --> 00:18:45.750
That's happened so many times.

00:18:45.750 --> 00:18:50.660
So when it came to this higher
stakes situation with Boston,

00:18:50.660 --> 00:18:53.897
it was just horrifying to think
of that family that was hurt.

00:18:53.897 --> 00:18:55.730
I'm not sure if you
guys all know the story.

00:18:55.730 --> 00:18:58.460
But basically, a suspect
was misidentified.

00:18:58.460 --> 00:19:03.200
And it was a student named
Sunil who had disappeared

00:19:03.200 --> 00:19:05.270
from his university.

00:19:05.270 --> 00:19:07.280
He looked--
physically, just kind

00:19:07.280 --> 00:19:10.670
of resembled one of the actual
suspects, the actual brothers.

00:19:10.670 --> 00:19:13.940
And by the time--

00:19:13.940 --> 00:19:15.710
his family was harassed.

00:19:15.710 --> 00:19:19.130
And they were already
in a place of mourning

00:19:19.130 --> 00:19:23.040
for having their son
having disappeared.

00:19:23.040 --> 00:19:26.240
His body was later found
floating in a river

00:19:26.240 --> 00:19:28.470
and in an unrelated death.

00:19:28.470 --> 00:19:31.910
So it was just this
horrifying thing

00:19:31.910 --> 00:19:35.600
that Reddit sort of happened
to-- because of the nature

00:19:35.600 --> 00:19:40.440
of that community and being able
to post anything anonymously,

00:19:40.440 --> 00:19:44.700
I think people got really
worked up about it.

00:19:44.700 --> 00:19:48.740
And I think the incident
really highlights

00:19:48.740 --> 00:19:50.630
how difficult it is
to be a moderator

00:19:50.630 --> 00:19:52.490
in a situation like that.

00:19:52.490 --> 00:19:54.530
Those moderators
were volunteers.

00:19:54.530 --> 00:19:56.301
They were-- by my
best estimation,

00:19:56.301 --> 00:19:57.800
I think a couple
of them were really

00:19:57.800 --> 00:20:01.130
young students themselves.

00:20:01.130 --> 00:20:03.470
Trying to keep up with
those instances of doxing

00:20:03.470 --> 00:20:05.400
and whatnot, it's
almost impossible

00:20:05.400 --> 00:20:07.080
when people jump
on it so quickly.

00:20:07.080 --> 00:20:09.930
And I think it
raises the question,

00:20:09.930 --> 00:20:13.650
how do we do content
management and community

00:20:13.650 --> 00:20:16.020
management in this modern era?

00:20:16.020 --> 00:20:18.150
How do you manage that
kind of bandwidth?

00:20:18.150 --> 00:20:20.550
Facebook has had this
question repeatedly.

00:20:20.550 --> 00:20:22.590
Twitter, obviously,
is grappling with it.

00:20:22.590 --> 00:20:26.800
And Reddit has a fraction of the
employees as those companies.

00:20:26.800 --> 00:20:29.010
It only has 400 and some.

00:20:29.010 --> 00:20:31.617
Is that weight all on
the volunteer moderators?

00:20:31.617 --> 00:20:33.450
SPEAKER: Well, I think
that's the other part

00:20:33.450 --> 00:20:35.760
of the social, maybe,
bad is when there's

00:20:35.760 --> 00:20:39.200
borderline illegal
or sometimes illegal

00:20:39.200 --> 00:20:41.880
subreddits that have popped
up over the years that

00:20:41.880 --> 00:20:44.410
can be started and how
moderators have to police that.

00:20:44.410 --> 00:20:45.993
And I know there's
an interesting part

00:20:45.993 --> 00:20:48.390
of the book of where they
had to almost make a decision

00:20:48.390 --> 00:20:49.470
and draw a bright line.

00:20:49.470 --> 00:20:50.880
And can you speak to--

00:20:50.880 --> 00:20:51.090
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN: Yeah.

00:20:51.090 --> 00:20:53.100
Which decision was it
that you're talking about?

00:20:53.100 --> 00:20:55.590
SPEAKER: I believe it was
with the jailbait and some

00:20:55.590 --> 00:20:56.377
of those other--

00:20:56.377 --> 00:20:57.960
CHRISTINE LAGORIO-CHAFKIN:
Well, is it

00:20:57.960 --> 00:21:00.750
the first decision that Ellen
Pao made when she was-- yes.

00:21:00.750 --> 00:21:01.320
There we go.

00:21:01.320 --> 00:21:04.509
So after Yishan Wong left--

00:21:04.509 --> 00:21:06.300
by the way, that's one
of my favorite lines

00:21:06.300 --> 00:21:07.509
in the book is that--

00:21:07.509 --> 00:21:09.050
and it's a direct
quote from Yishan--

00:21:09.050 --> 00:21:10.740
that his story of
leaving the company

00:21:10.740 --> 00:21:14.730
was unbelievable
because it's so weird.

00:21:14.730 --> 00:21:20.130
And after he left,
Ellen Pao became CEO.

00:21:20.130 --> 00:21:24.750
And she was already deep in
her "Kleiner Perkins" trial.

00:21:24.750 --> 00:21:30.201
She was set to testify while
she was at Reddit, and she did.

00:21:30.201 --> 00:21:31.950
And I think that
informed her a little bit

00:21:31.950 --> 00:21:34.980
in terms of where we need to
start drawing lines online.

00:21:34.980 --> 00:21:39.460
And I mean, it's always been
a tricky issue for Reddit

00:21:39.460 --> 00:21:43.590
because it's always been known
as a haven for free speech.

00:21:43.590 --> 00:21:46.260
And to say, no, we are
not, we are cutting off

00:21:46.260 --> 00:21:49.800
these noxious communities, was
a really, really tricky thing.

00:21:49.800 --> 00:21:54.030
So she basically tasked
her head community manager

00:21:54.030 --> 00:21:56.730
with identifying
five subreddits--

00:21:56.730 --> 00:21:58.980
say, OK, we're just
going to cut them off.

00:21:58.980 --> 00:22:02.820
And one of them, most
notably, was fatpeoplehate.

00:22:02.820 --> 00:22:04.740
That was a very
sizable community.

00:22:04.740 --> 00:22:07.710
And so on that
day, they actually

00:22:07.710 --> 00:22:11.190
did just make an announcement,
cut off the communities,

00:22:11.190 --> 00:22:14.460
managed those same
communities popping

00:22:14.460 --> 00:22:16.590
back up under new names--

00:22:16.590 --> 00:22:18.900
fatpeoplehate2,
wedislikefatpeople,

00:22:18.900 --> 00:22:20.920
or whatever.

00:22:20.920 --> 00:22:25.850
It wasn't super savvy, but
of course, people tried.

00:22:25.850 --> 00:22:29.920
After they cut off the next
waves, then they did see--

00:22:29.920 --> 00:22:32.310
and this was not until years
later that we could really

00:22:32.310 --> 00:22:34.050
document it-- but
researchers have

00:22:34.050 --> 00:22:37.210
found that the simple act
of cutting off those five

00:22:37.210 --> 00:22:41.350
first subreddits has improved
the quality of speech

00:22:41.350 --> 00:22:42.600
on Reddit throughout the site.

00:22:42.600 --> 00:22:46.370
You think of all this uncivil,
dis-civil discourse that's

00:22:46.370 --> 00:22:48.450
been plaguing the
internet right now,

00:22:48.450 --> 00:22:52.770
it actually demonstrably
improved that

00:22:52.770 --> 00:22:54.070
throughout the site.

00:22:54.070 --> 00:22:57.120
So years later-- and this wasn't
until I think a year or two ago

00:22:57.120 --> 00:23:00.390
that this research came out--

00:23:00.390 --> 00:23:04.860
it's shown that Ellen Pao did
accomplish what she set out to,

00:23:04.860 --> 00:23:08.110
despite the crazy
backlash to it.

00:23:08.110 --> 00:23:10.410
SPEAKER: So let's switch
gears to something good--

00:23:10.410 --> 00:23:13.630
the Reddit Gifts, which
is its own business.

00:23:13.630 --> 00:23:16.680
But I think the most recent stat
I saw was at the 10-year mark,

00:23:16.680 --> 00:23:19.680
it was $29 million
worth of gifts.

00:23:19.680 --> 00:23:22.050
